John Morse, president of Merriam-Webster, pointed out that "the most frequently looked up words are not the newest words, not the latest high-tech terms, not the cool new slang."<ref name="WriteNews" /> Instead, these top ten words correlated to breaking news stories and world events in 2003. The top word ''democracy'' correlated to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]] and the overthrow of [[Saddam Hussein]]'s regime,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Word of the Year |first=Scott |last=Bakalar |work=Word of Mouth |date=2007-12-19 |url=http://thewomblog.com/?p=1110 |accessdate=2008-06-04 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20080103085941/http://thewomblog.com/?p=1110 |archivedate=2008-01-03 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> ''quarantine'' to a [[SARS epidemic]], and ''matrix'' to the film ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]''.<ref name="WriteNews" />
