ry.reference.com/browse/defenestration |accessdate=2008-05-10}}</ref> |}
In 2004, blogs were becoming highly popular and began to influence mainstream media. During the twelve-month period that decides the word of the year, the term ''blog'' had the most requests for a definition or explanation, so a new entry was placed in Merriam-Webster's printed dictionary for 2005. The other words on this list, such as ''incumbent'', ''electoral'', and ''partisan'', were associated with major news events, such as the [[United States presidential election, 2004|United States presidential election of 2004]] or natural disasters that hit the US.<ref name="BBCblog">{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/4059291.stm | title = 'Blog' picked as word of the year: The term "blog" has been chosen as the top word of 2004 by a US dictionary publisher. | publisher = [[BBC News]] | date = 2004-12-01 | accessdate = 2007-12-29 }}</ref>
===2005=== {| class="wikitable" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name="mw07prev" /> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | [[wikt:integrity|integrity]] | ''([[noun]])'' Adherence to moral or ethic principles; incorruptibility.<ref name="Miller05" /> |- | <center>2</center> | [[wikt:refugee|refugee]] | ''(noun)'' One who flees for protection from danger or distress; one who flees to another country or place for safety.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=refugee |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |year=1991 |publisher=P.S.I. & Associates |page=280 |isbn=0-938261-79-7 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=refuge |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |year=1991 |publisher=P.S.I. & Associates |isbn=0-938261-79-7 |page=280}}</ref> |- | <center>3</center> | [[wikt:contempt|contempt]] | ''(noun)'' Willful disobedience to or open disrespect of a court, judge or legislative body.<ref name="Miller05" /> |- | <center>4</center> | [[wikt:filibuster|filibuster]] | ''(noun)'' Using delaying tactics in an attempt to delay or prevent action, especially in a legislative assembly.<ref name="Miller05" /> |- | <center>5</center> | [[wikt:insipid|insipid]] | ''([[adjective]])'' Lacking in taste; vapid, flat, dull, heavy, and spiritless.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=insipid |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |year=1991 |publisher=P.S.I. & Associates |page=180 |isbn=0-938261-79-7 }}</ref> |- | <center>6</center> | [[wikt:tsunami|tsunami]] | ''(noun)'' Very large ocean wave caused by an underwater earthquake or volcanic eruption.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=tsunami |encyclopedia=American Heritage Science Dictionary |year=2002 |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |accessdate=2008-04-21 |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/tsunami}}</ref> |- | <center>7</center> | [[wikt:pandemic|pandemic]] | ''(noun)'' Occurring over a wide geographic area; affecting a large population.<ref name="Miller05" /> |- | <center>8</center> | [[wikt:conclave|conclave]] | ''(noun)'' Assembly of [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinals]] to elect the [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[pope]]; a secret assembly.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=conclave |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |year=1991 |publisher=P.S.I.& Associates |isbn=0-938261-79-7 |page=61}}</ref> |- | <center>9</center> | [[wikt:levee|levee]] | ''(noun)'' A formal reception of guests, as in a royal court; a pier that provides a place to land at a river; an embankment that was made to prevent a river from overflowing.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=levee |encyclopedia=WordNet |edition=3.0 |year=2006 |publisher=[[Princeton University]] |accessdate=2008-04-27 |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/levee}}</ref> |- | <center>10</center> | [[wikt:inept|inept]] | ''(adjective)'' Not apt or fitting, inappropriate; lack of judgement, sense, or reason; foolish; bungling or clumsy; incompetent.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=inept |encyclopedia=The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language |edition=Fourth |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |year=2006 |accessdate=2008-04-27 |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/inept}}</ref> |}
For 2005, ''integrity'' was the most looked-up word in Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary.<ref>{{cite news |title=The words that made 2005 |first=Ruth |last=Walker |work=The Christian Science Monitor |date=2006-01-04 |page=18}}</ref> According to John Morse, President of Merriam-Webster, the word ''integrity'' slowly moved up the list to first place in 2005 because ethics scandals emerged around the United States regarding corporations, government, and sports,<ref name="solomon05" /> such as the [[CIA]] leak investigations, scandals in Congress, and disgraced athletes.<ref name="Miller05">{{cite news |title=Why 'integrity' was such a sought-after word this year ; It beat 'refugee' and 'contempt' as the most looked-up word of 2005, according to Merriam-Webster's online dictionary |first=Sara |last=Miller |work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date=2005-12-20 |page=02}}</ref>
[[Hurricane Katrina]], the [[Avian influenza|bird flu]], and the death of [[Pope John Paul II]] renewed public interest in words such as ''refugee,'' ''tsunami,'' ''pandemic,'' ''conclave,'' and ''levee.'' The word ''refugee'' was also a candidate for the [[American Dialect Society]]'s [[Word of the Year]]; according to Morse, the term gained notoriety as the entire country debated with how to describe people affected by Hurricane Katrina.<ref name="solomon05" /> The debate, over whether ''refugee'' was the proper term to describe displaced residents or whether the term was pejorative, summoned several Americans to look up the word in their dictionaries to form their own opinion. The word ''refugee'' received more queries in one month than most words in an entire year.<ref name="Miller05" /> The word ''insipid'' made the Top 10 list after [[Simon Cowell]] described [[Anthony Fedorov]]'s performance in ''[[American Idol]]'' as "pleasant, safe, and a little insipid."<ref name="solomon05">{{cite news |first=Wendy |last= Solomon |title=The Nation; 'Integrity' Often Questioned in '05; The most-checked word in Webster's online and slang like 'infosnacking' catch linguists' eyes. |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2005-12-25 }}</ref> At number 10 is ''inept'', a word that received a lot of attention after the days when [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] delivered a live prime time news conference that came to an awkward end when some television networks cut him off to return to their regularly scheduled programs.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dictionary reveals US 'word of the year' |work=China Daily |date=2005-12-12 |page=7}}</ref>
===2006=== {| class="wikitable" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name="mw07prev">{{cite web |url=http://www.m-w.com/info/07words_prev.htm |title= Previous Words of the Year |publisher=[[Merriam-Webster]] |year=2007 |accessdate=2007-12-29 }}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | [[wikt:truthiness|truthiness]] | ''([[noun]])'' Truth coming from the gut, not books; preferring to believe what you wish to believe, rather than what is known to be true.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dick |last=Meyer |title=The Truth Of Truthiness |work=CBS News |publisher=[[CBS]] |date=2006-12-12 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/12/12/opinion/meyer/main2250923.shtml |accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> |- | <center>2</center> | [[wikt:google|google]] | ''([[verb]])'' Using the [[Google]] search engine to look up information about a person.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2008 |title=google |encyclopedia=Webster's New Millennium Dictionary of English |publisher=[[Lexico]] |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/google |accessdate=2008-03-15}}</ref> |- | <center>3</center> | [[Wikt:decider|decider]] | ''(noun)'' A person who settles things in dispute or doubt.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=decide |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v 1.1 |publisher=[[Random House]] |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/decider }}</ref> |- | rowspan=3 |<center>4</center> | rowspan=3 |[[wikt:war|war]] | ''(noun)'' A contest of armed forces between nations, countries, or parties. |- | ''(verb)'' To be in conflict or state of opposition. |- | ''([[adjective]])'' Related to, of, belonging to, used in, or due to such a contest or conflict.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=1991 |title=War |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |publisher=P.S.I. & Associates |isbn=0-938261-79-7 |page=371}}</ref> |- | rowspan=2 |<center>5</center> | rowspan=2 |[[wikt:insurgent|insurgent]] | ''(noun)'' A person who rebels or rises against authority. |- | ''(adjective)'' Rising in revolt, refusing to accept authority.<ref name=insurgent>{{cite book |last= Shostak|first=Jerome |title= Vocabulary Workshop: Level F |edition= New |series=Vocabulary Workshop |year=2005 |publisher=William H. Sadlier |location=[[New York City]] |isbn=0-8215-7111-7 |pages=67 |chapter=6}}</ref> |- | <center>6</center> | [[wikt:terrorism|terrorism]] | ''(noun)'' Use of violence or threats to intimidate or coerce a person, especially for political purposes.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=terrorism |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v 1.1 |publisher=Random House |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/terrorism |accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref> |- | <center>7</center> | [[wikt:vendetta|vendetta]] | ''(noun)'' A blood feud;<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=1991 |title=Vendetta |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |publisher=P.S.I. & Associates |isbn=0-938261-79-7 |page=365}}</ref> prolonged and bitter feud, rivalry, or contention.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=vendetta |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v 1.1 |publisher=Random House |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/vendetta |accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref> |- | <center>8</center> | [[wikt:sectarian|sectarian]] | ''(adjective)'' Pertaining to factions united under one doctrine, such as religious denominations;<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=sectarian |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v 1.1 |publisher=Random House |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/sectarian |accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=sect |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v 1.1 |publisher=Random House |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/sect |accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref> narrow-minded.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=sectarian |encyclopedia=The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language |edition=Fourth |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/sectarian |accessdate=2008-03-19}}</ref> |- | <center>9</center> | [[Wikt:quagmire|quagmire]] | ''(noun)'' Soft, wet, boggy land;<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=1991 |title=Quagmire |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |publisher=P.S.I. & Associates |isbn=0-938261-79-7 |page=272}}</ref> a situation from which extrication is difficult.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=quagmire |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v 1.1 |publisher=Random House |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/quagmire |accessdate=2008-03-24}}</ref> |- | <center>10</center> | [[Wikt:corruption|corruption]] | ''(noun)'' Lack of integrity or honesty; decay; impairment of virtue and moral principles; undermining moral integrity; inducement by a public official with improper means to violate duties, for example, bribery.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=corruption |encyclopedia=WordNet |edition=3.0 |publisher=[[Princeton University]] |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/corruption |accessdate=2008-03-24}}</ref> |}
After online visitors chose ''truthiness'' in a five-to-one majority vote as the Word of the Year of 2006,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/06words.htm | title = Merriam-Webster's Words of the Year 2006 | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | year = 2007 | accessdate = 2007-12-29 }}</ref> Merriam-Webster received a large amount of publicity.<ref name="NYT">{{cite news|first=Andrew Adam |last=Newman |title=How Dictionaries Define Publicity: the Word of the Year |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher= |date=2007-12-10 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/10/business/media/10oxford.html |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uOOyKmZt?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/10/business/media/10oxford.html?_r=1 |archivedate=2010-11-20 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> This was the first year in which Merriam-Webster used online voting to decide its Word of the Year.<ref name="Bierma06" /> The term was created by [[Stephen Colbert]] on [[Comedy Central]] in ''[[The Colbert Report]]'''s first episode,<ref>{{cite news |first= |last=Anonymous |title= Truthiness--The Word of the Year |work= News for You |publisher= |date=2007-01-24}}</ref> which took place on October 2005,<ref>{{cite news |title=Word of year has ring of ... you know |last=[[The Associated Press]] |work=The Grand Rapids Press |date=2006-12-12 |page=A.6}}</ref> to describe things that he fervently believes to be the case regardless of the facts.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Independent]] |date=2007-10-20 |title=Vote Colbert! (The Candidate Running for Both Parties)}}</ref> In addition, ''truthiness'' became the [[American Dialect Society]]'s [[Word of the Year]] for 2005.<ref name="Bierma06">{{cite news |first= Nathan |last=Bierma |title=Talking about the word of the year |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |publisher= |date=2006-12-27 }}</ref>
===2007=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name="mw07">{{cite web |url = http://www.m-w.com/info/07words.htm |title = Merriam-Webster's Word of the Year 2007 |publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] |year = 2007 |accessdate = 2009-03-16}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | [[Wikt:w00t|w00t]] | ''([[interjection]])'' Expressing joy.<ref name="mw07"/> |- | <center>2</center> | [[Wikt:facebook|Facebook]] | ''([[verb]])'' To post a picture or other information to profile pages at the trademarked social networking website [[Facebook]].<ref name="AFP" /> |- | <center>3</center> | [[Wikt:conundrum|conundrum]] | ''([[noun]])'' A riddle whose answer is or involves a [[pun]]; question or problem with only a conjectural answer; intricate and difficult problem.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=conundrum |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/conundrum |accessdate=2009-03-16 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>4</center> | [[wikt:quixotic|quixotic]] | ''([[adjective]])'' Foolishly impractical especially in the pursuit of ideals; loftily romantic or extravagantly chivalrous; capricious or unpredictable.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=quixotic |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/quixotic |accessdate=2009-03-16 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>5</center> | [[Wikt:blamestorm|blamestorm]] | ''(verb)'' To hold a discussion in order to assign blame to a person for a failure.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2008 |title=Blamestorming |encyclopedia=Webster's New Millennium Dictionary of English |publisher=[[Lexico]] |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/search?r=2&q=blamestorming |accessdate=2008-03-08}}</ref> |- | <center>6</center> | [[Wikt:sardoodledom|sardoodledom]] | ''(noun)'' "A play with an overly contrived and melodramatic plot."<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Quinion |title=Sardoodledom |work=World Wide Words |url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/weirdwords/ww-sar2.htm |date=2007-12-15 |accessdate=2008-03-08}}</ref> |- | <center>7</center> | [[wikt:apathetic|apathetic]] | ''(adjective)'' No feeling or passion, indifferent.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=1991 |title=Apathetic |encyclopedia=Webster's Expanded Dictionary |publisher=P.S.I. & Associates |isbn=0-938261-79-7 |page=17}}</ref> |- | <center>8</center> | [[Wikt:Pecksniffian|Pecksniffian]] | ''(adjective)'' Hypocritically benevolent.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=Pecksniffian |encyclopedia=American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language |edition=Fourth|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/pecksniffian |accessdate=2008-03-08}}</ref> |- | <center>9</center> | [[wikt:hypocrite|hypocrite]] | ''(noun)'' Person who pretends to have virtues, beliefs, or principles that he or she does not actually possess.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=Hyprocrit |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v 1.1 |publisher=[[Random House]]|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/hypocrite |accessdate=2008-03-08}}</ref> |- | <center>10</center> | [[wikt:charlatan|charlatan]] | ''(noun)'' A person who pretends to have more knowledge and skill than he or she actually possesses.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2006 |title=charlatan |encyclopedia=Dictionary.com Unabridged |edition=v. 1.1 |publisher=[[Random House]] |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/charlatan |accessdate=2008-03-08}}</ref> |}
John Morse, President of Merriam-Webster, said that the word ''w00t'' was a good choice because it "blends whimsy and new technology".<ref name="ap">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=3984898 |title=Merriam-Webster's Word of '07: 'W00t' |first=Stephanie |last=Reitz |publisher=ABCNews Internet Ventures |work=ABC News |date=2007-12-11 |accessdate=2008-06-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605210357/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=3984898 |archivedate=June 5, 2008 }}</ref> Spelled with two zeros in [[leetspeak]], ''w00t'' reflects a new direction in the English language led by a generation raised on [[video games]] and [[cell phone]] [[text messaging]].<ref>{{cite news |title="w00t" crowned word of year by U.S. dictionary |first=Jason |last=Szep |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2007-12-11 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/internetNews/idUSN1155159520071212 |accessdate=2008-06-03}}</ref> While the word itself has not been published in its printed dictionary yet, Merriam-Webster claims that its presence in the Open Dictionary and the honors it's been awarded gives ''w00t'' a better chance at becoming an official word.<ref>{{cite news |title=Word-of-the-Year Ritual Pauses for Puzzlement |first=Mike |last=Nizza |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2007-12-13 |accessdate=2008-06-03 |url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/12/13/word-of-the-year-ritual-pauses-for-puzzlement/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Woot' Named Merriam-Webster's Word of the Year |url=http://blog.wired.com/games/2007/12/woot-named-merr.html |accessdate=2008-06-20 |first=Susan |last=Arendt |date=2007-12-12 |work=Wired |publisher=CondéNet}}</ref> It originally became popular in online gaming forums and is now used as an expression of excitement and joy. The word is also considered an acronym in the online gaming world for the phrase ''We owned the other team.''<ref name="AFP">{{cite news |title="w00t" voted Merriam-Webster word of the year |publisher=[[Agence France-Presse]] |work=[[Google News]] |date=2007-12-12 |url=http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5ileUw1tWfWTY4wpRO8Ak67PixHfQ |accessdate=2008-03-08}}</ref> This word was also used in the 1990 film [[Pretty Woman]] when [[Julia Roberts]] exclaimed "Woot, woot, woot!" to her date's friends during a polo match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Merriam-Webster's Word of '07: 'W00t'; Winner in Merriam-Webster's Online Word of the Year Poll Something for Gamers to "W00t" About |first=Stephanie |last=Reitz |date=December 11, 2007 |work=ABC News |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=3984898 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112045700/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=3984898 |archivedate=January 12, 2008}}</ref>
Placing second in 2007's contest, ''facebook'' created an unofficial verb out of the website [[Facebook]].<ref name="AFP" /> Founded in 2004, Facebook is a social network that allows its users to create a profile page and forge links with other friends and acquaintances.<ref>{{cite news |first=Brad |last=Stone |title=Facebook |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=2007-12-07 |accessdate=2008-03-17 |url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/facebook_inc/index.html?inline=nyt-org }}</ref>
===2008=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name="mw08">{{cite web |url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/08words.htm |title = Merriam-Webster's Word of the Year 2008 |publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] |year = 2008 |accessdate = 2009-03-05}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | [[bailout]] | ''([[noun]])'' A rescue from financial distress.<ref name="mw08"/> |- | <center>2</center> | [[Wikt:vet|vet]] | ''([[verb]])'' To provide veterinary care for an animal or medical care for a person; to subject a person or animal to a physical examination or checkup; to subject to expert appraisal or correction; to evaluate for possible approval or acceptance.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=vet |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/vet |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>3</center> | [[socialism]] | ''(noun)'' economic or political theory advocating collective or governmental ownership and administration of the means of production and distribution of goods; society in which there is no private property; a stage of society in [[Marxist theory]] transitional between capitalism and communism and distinguished by unequal distribution of goods and pay according to work done.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=socialism |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/socialism |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>4</center> | [[wikt:maverick|maverick]] | ''(noun)'' unbranded range animal, especially a motherless calf; an independent individual who does not go along with a group or party.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=maverick |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/maverick |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>5</center> | [[bipartisan]] | ''([[adjective]])'' of, relating to, or involving members of two parties; specifically, marked by or involving cooperation, agreement, and compromise between two major political parties.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=bipartisan |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/bipartisan |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>6</center> | [[Wikt:trepidation|trepidation]] | ''(noun)'' A tremor; apprehension.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=trepidation |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/trepidation |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>7</center> | [[wikt:precipice|precipice]] | ''(noun)'' Very steep or overhanging place; a hazardous situation.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=precipice |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/precipice |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>8</center> | [[Wikt:rogue|rogue]] | ''(noun)'' Vagrant or tramp; dishonest, worthless, or mischievous person; horse inclined to shirk or misbehave; individual with a chance and usually inferior biological variation.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=rogue |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/rogue |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>9</center> | [[misogyny]] | ''(noun)'' Hatred of women.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=misogyny |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/misogyny |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>10</center> | [[wikt:turmoil|turmoil]] | ''(noun)'' a state or condition of extreme confusion, agitation, or commotion.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=turmoil |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/turmoil |accessdate=2009-03-06 |year=2009 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |}
===2009=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name="mw09">{{cite web |url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/09words.htm |title = Merriam-Webster's Word of the Year 2009 |publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] |year = 2009 |accessdate = 2009-02-22}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | [[Wikt:admonish|admonish]] | ''([[verb]])'' to express warning or disapproval to especially in a gentle, earnest, or solicitous manner<ref name="mw09"/> |- | <center>2</center> | [[Wikt:emaciated|emaciated]] | ''([[verb]])'' to have wasted away physically<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=emaciated |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/emaciated |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>3</center> | [[Wikt:empathy|empathy]] | ''([[noun]])'' the action of understanding, being aware of, being sensitive to, and vicariously experiencing the feelings, thoughts, and experience of another of either the past or present without having the feelings, thoughts, and experience fully communicated in an objectively explicit manner; ''also'' : the capacity for this<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=empathy |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/empathy |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>4</center> | [[wikt:furlough|furlough]] | ''([[noun]])'' a leave of absence from duty granted especially to a soldier; ''also'' : a document authorizing such a leave of absence.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=furlough |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/furlough |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>5</center> | [[Wikt:inaugurate|inaugurate]] | ''([[verb]])'' to induct into an office with suitable ceremonies<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=inaugurate |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/inaugurate |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>6</center> | [[Wikt:nugatory|nugatory]] | ''([[adjective]])'' of little or no consequence<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=nugatory |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/nugatory |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>7</center> | [[wikt:pandemic|pandemic]] | ''([[adjective]])'' occurring over a wide geographic area and affecting an exceptionally high proportion of the population<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=pandemic |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/pandemic |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>8</center> | [[Wikt:philanderer|philanderer]] | ''([[noun]])'' : one who has casual or illicit sex with a woman or with many women<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=philanderer |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/philanderer |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>9</center> | [[wikt:repose|repose]] | ''([[verb]])'' to lie at rest<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=repose |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/repose |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |- | <center>10</center> | [[wikt:rogue|rogue]] | ''([[adjective]])'' corrupt, dishonest<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Online Dictionary |title=rogue |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/rogue |accessdate=2010-02-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Merriam-Webster}}</ref> |}
===2010=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref>{{cite web|title=Words of the Year 2010|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/10words.htm|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- |<center>1</center> |[[wikt:austerity|austerity]] |''([[noun]])'' Severity of manners or life; extreme rigor or strictness; harsh discipline. |- |<center>2</center> |[[wikt:pragmatic|pragmatic]] |''([[adjective]])'' Practical, concerned with making decisions and actions that are useful in practice, not just theory. |- |<center>3</center> |[[wikt:moratorium|moratorium]] |''([[noun]])'' A suspension of an ongoing activity. |- |<center>4</center> |[[wikt:socialism|socialism]] |''([[noun]])'' Any of various economic and political philosophies that support social equality, collective decision-making, distribution of income based on contribution and public ownership of productive capital and natural resources, as advocated by socialists. |- |<center>5</center> |[[wikt:bigot|bigot]] |''([[noun]])'' One who is obstinately or intolerantly devoted to his or her own opinions and prejudices. |- |<center>6</center> |[[wikt:doppelganger|doppelganger]] |''([[noun]])'' A ghostly double of a living person, especially one that haunts such a person; An evil twin; A remarkably similar double; A person who has the same name as another; A fantastic monster that takes the forms of people, usually after killing them. |- |<center>7</center> |[[wikt:shellacking|shellacking]] |''([[noun]])'' A heavy defeat, drubbing, or beating; used particularly in sports and political contexts. |- |<center>8</center> |[[wikt:ebullient|ebullient]] |''([[adjective]])'' Boiling, agitated; enthusiastic, high-spirited. |- |<center>9</center> |[[wikt:dissident|dissident]] |''([[noun]])'' A person who formally opposes the current political structure, opposes the political group in power, opposes the policies of the political group in power, or opposes current laws. |- |<center>10</center> |[[wikt:furtive|furtive]] |''([[adjective]])'' Stealthy; Exhibiting guilty or evasive secrecy. |}
''Austerity'' was the most searched-for word of 2010. Interest in the word reached its highest point around May 1,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/trend-watch/2010/05/01/ |title=Austerity |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref> the day the Greek government announced a series of austerity measures, but its popularity remained strong throughout the year. Peter Sokolowski, Merriam-Webster editor-at-large, said: "''Austerity'' clearly resonates with many people. We often hear it used in the context of government measures, but we also apply it to our own personal finances and what is sometimes called the new normal." [[Barack Obama]] used the word ''shellacking'' in November 2010, when acknowledging his party's losses in the [[United States elections, 2010|US mid-term elections]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/trend-watch/2010/11/03/ |title=Shellacking |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref> and lookups of ''ebullient'' peaked in October, as [[2010 Copiapó mining accident|thirty-three Chilean miners]] were successfully rescued after 69 days trapped underground.<ref name=mw12/>
===2011=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name=mw11>{{cite web|title=Words of the Year 2011|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/2011words.htm|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- |<center>1</center> |[[wikt:pragmatic|pragmatic]] |''([[adjective]])'' Practical, concerned with making decisions and actions that are useful in practice, not just theory. |- |<center>2</center> |[[wikt:ambivalence|ambivalence]] |''([[noun]])'' The coexistence of opposing attitudes or feelings (such as love and hate) towards a person, object or idea; A state of uncertainty or indecisiveness. |- |<center>3</center> |[[wikt:insidious|insidious]] |''([[adjective]])'' Producing harm in a stealthy, often gradual, manner; Intending to entrap; alluring but harmful. |- |<center>4</center> |[[wikt:didactic|didactic]] |''([[adjective]])'' Instructive or intended to teach or demonstrate, especially with regard to morality; Excessively moralizing. |- |<center>5</center> |[[wikt:austerity|austerity]] |''([[noun]])'' Severity of manners or life; extreme rigor or strictness; harsh discipline. |- |<center>6</center> |[[wikt:diversity|diversity]] |''([[noun]])'' The quality of being diverse or different; difference or unlikeness. |- |<center>7</center> |[[wikt:capitalism|capitalism]] |''([[noun]])'' A socio-economic system based on private property rights, including the private ownership of resources or capital, with economic decisions made largely through the operation of a market unregulated by the state. |- |<center>8</center> |[[wikt:socialism|socialism]] |''([[noun]])'' Any of various economic and political philosophies that support social equality, collective decision-making, distribution of income based on contribution and public ownership of productive capital and natural resources, as advocated by socialists. |- |<center>9</center> |[[wikt:vitriol|vitriol]] |''([[noun]])'' Bitterly abusive language. |- |<center>10</center> |[[List of French words and phrases used by English speakers#A|après moi le déluge]] |''(foreign term)'' "After me, the deluge", a remark attributed to [[Louis XV]] of France in reference to the impending end of a functioning French monarchy and predicting the French Revolution. |}
The word ''pragmatic'' was looked up on Merriam-Webster's website an unprecedented number of times in 2011.<ref name=mw11/> Although the popularity of the word wasn't linked to any specific event, it received the greatest amount of interest in the latter half of the year, as the [[United States Congress]] introduced the [[Budget Control Act of 2011|Budget Control Act]], and its [[Supercommittee]] began to craft deficit-reduction plans.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reitz |first=Stephanie |url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/scene/article.aspx?subjectid=67&articleid=20111226_13_D6_Whenth344892 |title=Merriam-Webster picks 'Pragmatic' as Word of Year |work=Tulsa World |date=December 26, 2011 |accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref> ''Ambivalence'' was also a popular word throughout the year; John Moore, President of Merriam-Webster, remarked: "We think it reflects the public attitude toward a wide range of issues, including the economy, the ongoing debates in Washington, the presidential election, and most recently the race for the Republican Party nomination." The term ''vitriol'' was used frequently in the wake of the January 2011 [[2011 Tucson shooting|Tucson shooting]], which led to a national debate about political rhetoric.<ref name=mw11/>
In November 2011, political commentator [[David Gergen]] rounded off a CNN article (entitled "Have they gone nuts in Washington?") with the phrase "après moi, le déluge".<ref>{{cite news |last=Gergen |first=David |url=http://www.cnn.co.uk/2011/11/21/opinion/gergen-reckless-congress/index.html |title=Have they gone nuts in Washington? |publisher=CNN |date=November 21, 2011 |accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref> The expression, attributed to [[Louis XV]], typifies the attitude of those who don't care about the future, because they won't be around to face the consequences of their actions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/trend-watch/2011/11/23/ |title=Après moi le déluge |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref>
===2012=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name=mw12>{{cite web|title=Words of the Year 2012|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/2012words.htm|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | rowspan="2" |<center>1</center> |[[wikt:socialism|socialism]] |''([[noun]])'' Any of various economic and political philosophies that support social equality, collective decision-making, distribution of income based on contribution and public ownership of productive capital and natural resources, as advocated by socialists. |- |[[wikt:capitalism|capitalism]] |''([[noun]])'' A socio-economic system based on private property rights, including the private ownership of resources or capital, with economic decisions made largely through the operation of a market unregulated by the state. |- |<center>2</center> |[[wikt:touché|touché]] |''([[interjection]])'' An acknowledgement of the success, appropriateness or superiority of an argument or discussion. |- |<center>3</center> |[[wikt:bigot|bigot]] |''([[noun]])'' One who is obstinately or intolerantly devoted to his or her own opinions and prejudices. |- |<center>4</center> |[[wikt:marriage|marriage]] |''([[noun]])'' The state of being married; A union of two or more people that creates a family tie and carries legal and/or social rights and responsibilities; A ceremony in which people wed. |- |<center>5</center> |[[wikt:democracy|democracy]] |''([[noun]])'' Rule by the people, especially as a form of government, either directly or through elected representatives; A government under the direct or representative rule of the people of its jurisdiction; Belief in political freedom and equality; the "spirit of democracy". |- |<center>6</center> |[[wikt:professionalism|professionalism]] |''([[noun]])'' The status, methods, character or standards expected of a professional or of a professional organization, such as reliability, discretion, evenhandedness, and fair play. |- |<center>7</center> |[[wikt:globalization|globalization]] |''([[noun]])'' The process of going to a more interconnected world; The process of making world economy dominated by capitalist models. |- |<center>8</center> |[[wikt:malarkey|malarkey]] |''([[noun]])'' Nonsense; rubbish. |- |<center>9</center> |[[wikt:schadenfreude|schadenfreude]] |''([[noun]])'' Malicious enjoyment derived from observing someone else's misfortune. |- |<center>10</center> |[[wikt:meme|meme]] |''([[noun]])'' Any unit of cultural information, such as a practice or idea, that is transmitted verbally or by repeated action from one mind to another; A thought, idea, joke, or concept that spreads online, often virally, in the form of e.g. an image, a video, an email, an animation, or music. |}
The popularity of many of the words on Merriam-Webster's 2012 list were influenced by the commentary and debate that surrounded that year's [[United States presidential election, 2012|US presidential election]]. ''Socialism'' and ''capitalism'' were frequently referred to during the party conventions and the televised debates; interest in ''socialism'' spiked on the day of the election – November 6, 2012.<ref name=mw12/> The word ''malarkey'' was used several times by [[Joe Biden]] during his [[United States vice-presidential debate, 2012|vice-presidential debate]] with [[Paul Ryan]] on October 11,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/trend-watch/2012/10/11/ |title=Malarkey |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref> and ''meme'' captured the public imagination after a remark made by [[Mitt Romney]] about "[[binders full of women]]", on October 16, went viral.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/trend-watch/2012/10/18/ |title=Meme |publisher=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=February 3, 2013}}</ref>
''Touché'' remained a popular word throughout the year. This was partly as a result of a new technology of the same name being announced by [[Disney Research]]; however, John Morse, President of Merriam-Webster, suggested that ''touché'' was "simply a word enjoying a period of increased popular use, perhaps as a byproduct of the growing amount of verbal jousting in our culture, especially through social media".<ref name=mw12/>
===2013=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name=mw13>{{cite web|title=Word of the Year 2013|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/2013-word-of-the-year.htm|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> |[[wikt:science|science]] |''([[noun]])'' Knowledge about or study of the natural world based on facts learned through experiments and observation. |- |<center>2</center> |[[wikt:cognitive|cognitive]] |''([[adjective]])'' Of, relating to, being, or involving conscious intellectual activity. |- |<center>3</center> |[[wikt:rapport|rapport]] |''([[noun]])'' A friendly relationship. |- |<center>4</center> |[[wikt:communication|communication]] |''([[noun]])'' The act or process of using words, sounds, signs, or behaviors to express or exchange information or to express your ideas, thoughts, feelings, etc., to someone else. |- |<center>5</center> |[[wikt:niche|niche]] |''([[noun]])'' A job, activity, etc., that is very suitable for someone; The situation in which a business's products or services can succeed by being sold to a particular kind or group of people |- |<center>6</center> |[[wikt:ethic|ethic]] |''([[noun]])'' Rules of behavior based on ideas about what is morally good and bad. |- |<center>7</center> |[[wikt:paradox|paradox]] |''([[noun]])'' Something (such as a situation) that is made up of two opposite things and that seems impossible but is actually true or possible. |- |<center>8</center> |[[wikt:visceral|visceral]] |''([[adjective]])'' Coming from strong emotions and not from logic or reason. |- |<center>9</center> |[[wikt:integrity|integrity]] |''([[noun]])'' The quality of being honest and fair; The state of being complete or whole. |- |<center>10</center> |[[wikt:metaphor|metaphor]] |''([[noun]])'' a word or phrase for one thing that is used to refer to another thing in order to show or suggest that they are similar; An object, activity, or idea that is used as a symbol of something else |}
The popularity of the word [[science]] in 2013 was driven by debates around [[climate change]] and science in education. Further debates around [[pseudoscience]] and whether science can answer all of life's questions further drove its popularity.
[[Cognitive|Cognitive's]] popularity was principally driven by ongoing issues with relation to [[concussion]] in American professional sports. The popularity of [[rapport]] and [[communication]] was principally driven by [[Edward Snowden|Edward Snowden's]] revelations around the [[National Security Agency|NSA's]] [[Global surveillance disclosure|global surveillance]].<ref name=mw13/>
===2014=== {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name=mw14>{{cite web|title=Word of the Year 2014|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/info/2014-word-of-the-year.htm|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=December 27, 2014}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition<ref>{{cite web|title=Merriam-Webster Online|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com|website=http://www.merriam-webster.com|publisher=Merriam-Webster Dictionaries|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> |- | <center>1</center> |[[wikt:culture|culture]] |''([[noun]])'' The beliefs, customs, arts, etc., of a particular society, group, place, or time. |- |<center>2</center> |[[wikt:nostalgia|nostalgia]] |''([[noun]])'' Pleasure and sadness that is caused by remembering something from the past and wishing that you could experience it again. |- |<center>3</center> |[[wikt:insidious|insidious]] |''([[adjective]])'' Causing harm in a way that is gradual or not easily noticed. |- |<center>4</center> |[[wikt:legacy|legacy]] |''([[noun]])'' Something that happened in the past or that comes from someone in the past. |- |<center>5</center> |[[wikt:feminism|feminism]] |''([[noun]])'' The belief that men and women should have equal rights and opportunities |- |<center>6</center> |[[wikt:je ne sais quoi|je ne sais quoi]] |''([[noun]])'' A pleasant quality that is hard to describe. |- |<center>7</center> |[[wikt:innovation|innovation]] |''([[noun]])'' A new idea, device, or method; the act or process of introducing new ideas, devices, or methods. |- |<center>8</center> |[[wikt:surreptitious|surreptitious]] |''([[adjective]])'' Done in a secret way. |- |<center>9</center> |[[wikt:autonomy|autonomy]] |''([[noun]])'' The state of existing or acting separately from others; the power or right of a country, group, etc., to govern itself. |- |<center>10</center> |[[wikt:morbidity|morbidity]] |''([[noun]])'' The quality or state of being [[wikt:morbid|morbid]] |} <ref name=mw14/>
=== 2015 === {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/words-at-play/word-of-the-year-2015|title=Gallery: Word of the Year 2015|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | -[[wikt:-ism|ism]] |''([[suffix]])'' A suffix that forms abstract nouns of action, state, condition, doctrine |- |<center>2</center> |[[wikt:socialism|Socialism]] |''([[noun]])'' Any of various economic and political theories advocating collective or governmental ownership and administration of the means of production and distribution of goods |- |<center>3</center> |[[wikt:fascism|Fascism]] |''([[noun]])'' A political philosophy, movement, or regime (as that of the Fascisti) that exalts nation and often race above the individual and that stands for a centralized autocratic government headed by a dictatorial leader |- |<center>4</center> |[[wikt:racism|Racism]] |''([[noun]])'' A belief that race is the primary determinant of human traits and capacities and that racial differences produce an inherent superiority of a particular race |- |<center>5</center> |[[wikt:feminism|Feminism]] |''([[noun]])'' The belief that men and women should have equal rights and opportunities |- |<center>6</center> |[[wikt:communism|Communism]] |''([[noun]])'' A theory advocating elimination of private property; a system in which goods are owned in common and are available to all as needed |- |<center>7</center> |[[wikt:capitalism|Capitalism]] |''([[noun]])'' An economic system characterized by private or corporate ownership of capital goods, by investments that are determined by private decision, and by prices, production, and the distribution of goods that are determined mainly by competition in a free market |- |<center>8</center> |[[wikt:terrorism|Terrorism]] |''([[noun]])'' The systematic use of terror especially as a means of coercion |- |<center>9</center> |[[wikt:marriage|Marriage]] |''([[noun]])'' The legally or formally recognized union of a man and a woman (or, in some jurisdictions, two people of the same sex) as partners in a relationship |- |<center>10</center> |[[wikt:hypocrite|Hypocrite]] |''([[noun]])'' A person who acts in contradiction to his or her stated beliefs or feelings |} The suffix ''-ism'' goes all the way back to Ancient Greek, and was used in Latin and medieval French on its way to English. Originally, it turned a verb into a noun: think of ''baptize'' and ''baptism, criticize'' and ''criticism,'' or ''plagiarize'' and ''plagiarism.'' It has since acquired many other uses, including identifying a religion or practice (''Calvinism, vegetarianism''), a prejudice based on a specific quality (''sexism, ageism''), an adherence to a system (''stoicism, altruism''), a condition based on excess of something (''alcoholism''), or a characteristic feature or trait (''colloquialism'').<ref name=":0" />
=== 2016 === {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/words-at-play/woty2016-top-looked-up-words-surreal|title=Word of the Year 2016}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | [[wikt:surreal|Surreal]] |''([[adjective]])'' Marked by the intense irrational reality of a dream |}
=== 2017 === {| class="wikitable" width="99%" ! width="5%" |Rank ! width="10%" |Word<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/words-at-play/word-of-the-year-2017-feminism|title=Merriam-Webster's 2017 Words of the Year}}</ref> ! width="85%" |Definition |- | <center>1</center> | [[wikt:feminism|Feminism]] |''([[noun]])'' The theory of the political, economic, and social equality of the sexes |}
